{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254632/1930073001/0022.xml":{"full_text":"22\nSpectator Urges Trading Element Use Caution in Making Committments\nBULLISH FORCES WEAKEN,\nCURRENT REPORTS SAT\nInability to Attract Public Support and Per\nsistent Bearish Reports Aid in Stopping\nY Drives; Canadian Election Cited\ni\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nGo slow and easy for the next few days at least. That\u2019s\nSpectator\u2019s advice. It looks as though a good deal of stock is\nbeing sold under the strength in various groups, as the utilities.\nPersistent reports that the bull forces are becoming a bit\ndiscouraged are scattered. They haven't been able to attract\nany public following to speak of. In addition they are being\nhit with bearish news from all sides.\nYesterday the conservatives in Canada, threatening this coun\ntry with a loss in business, followed during the course of the\nday by a break in wheat to new low ground. Even the ardent\nbulls won\u2019t fly in the teeth of the winds. They are very likely\nto let prices take their own course.\nSpectator isn\u2019t bearish, but just cautious, he feels that stocks\nmay be knocked off a good deal more and recommends getting\nin shape to take advantage of buying opportunities.\n\u201cBr&ssbands\u201d\nPools have been doing a lot of\nballyhoo recently, most of them\nhave not been getting anywhere\nin particular, the public has been\nvery coy and suspicious. The\nHelvinator pool was the latest to\ngo in for the \u201cbrass-band\u201d tip\nping the stock all over the street\nyesterday. The company\u2019s past\nrecord is against it, even though\nearnings took a jump this year.\nThe Briggs pool was successful\nin marking up the stock over 5\npoints since it was first men\ntioned here, but it is about\nwashed up, I hear. The move in\nHahn never got anywhere. Ac\ntivity in commercial solvents is\nover, I understand. I advise\nprofit-taking in these stocks for\nthe time being.\nUnited Biscuit\u2019s earnings are\nexpected to reach $5 a share this\nyear against $4.39 on a smaller\namount of stock outstanding in\n1929. The last half of the year\nordinarily brings a rise in profits.\nThe current dividend is $1.60,\nand well-informed quarters ex\npect an increase within the next\nyear if earnings are maintained.\nStill in the Air\nI am told that General Motors\nmade an offer to acquire United\nAircraft, but the bid was turned\ndown flat. Acquisition of air\ncraft by Motors would not sur\nprise the Street, as it is expecting\nthe latter to become an aviation\ngiant some day. The rub, as I\nhear it, is that the largest air\ncraft stockholders are bullish on\nthe company\u2019s long-term outlook\nand predict sky-high prices for\nthe stock in a few years. There\nhas been good buying in aircraft\non reactions, and I understand\nthat one investment trust has\ntaken a big long position.\nTransamerica got an unkind re\nception on the big board, meet\ning with pressure almost from\nthe start. It has been one of\nthe \u201cweak sisters\u201d the last two\ndays. I hear that the stock\u2019s\nbook value is well below current\nprices. Inter-Continental Corpo\nration, an investment trust it\ncontrols, showed a comparatively\ngood portfolio in its report. It is\nstuck with a good deal of stock,\nnotably Marine Midland, Ana\nconda and Texas Corporation, at\nmuch higher levels, but it also\nhas a lot of good securities well\nunder the market.\nLow Steam\nSouthern Railway and Union\nPacific broke wide open and car\nDECLINE SEEN IN\nSTORE SALES\nReports from 643 department\nstores in 266 cities to the Federal\nReserve Banks in their respective\ndistricts show that aggregate:\nsales for the month of June were 1\n10 per cent lower than in the\ncorresponding month of last year.\nFor the six months ended June\n30 last, total sales were 5 per\ncent less than in the first half\nOs 1929.\nDepartment stores in New York j\ncity showed a decline of 5 per j\ncent in sales for the month of!\nJune, but the aggegrate for the'\nsix months\u2019 period was unchanged\nfrom that of the corresponding\nperiod a year ago.\nThe largest declines were re\nported by Cleveland. Chicago and\nSt. Louis, where each city showed\n8 13 per cent drop in sales for\nJune. Philadelphia was close be\nhind with 12 per cent less for\nthe month. For the six months\nperiod. Chicago reported the\nheaviest drop, losing 11 per cent\nas compared with last year.\nAustralia Triples\nDuties on Lu \u2019er\nAustralia has tripled her im\nport duty on Douglas fir. un\ndressed logs, increasing the rate\nfrom 10 to 30 per cent ad\nvalorem the Commerce Depart\nbmbl n\u00bb \u00abdvued yesterday. I\nWASHINGTON NEWS\nried the rest of the fails along.\nThe former\u2019s decline to a new\nlow for the year was explained\nin its six-months\u2019 report, show\ning 36 cents a share earned on\nthe common against an $8 an\nnual dividend rate. Officials have\ninsisted that the dividend was\nsafe but evidently the street is\nskeptical. Railroad earnings have\nmade a sorry showing so far in\n1930 and can hardly expect to\ncome anywhere near 1929, even\nwith a rebound in the closing\nmonths of the year. However,\nrails of the caliber of Atchison,\nCentral, Union Pacific, Pennsyl\nvania and ethers have oodles of\ncash and can easily maintain\ntheir present dividends. The\nleading carriers will attract new\ninvestment buying if they go\nmuch lower, and I. believe they\nare a buy anywhere near their\nlows for the year.\nA floor trader reported good\nbuying in Standard Gas and Elec\ntric. Loss of the minority action\nagainst the merger with Standard\nPower and Light was probably\nan influence. The stock is selling\npretty high on an earnings basis.\nWell informed interests expect\nStandard Gas to make an offer\nfor the A stock of Louisville Gas,\nNorthern States Power, and other\nof its affiliates, but nothing im\nmediate is in the offing.\nHere and There\nThe old story of a deal with\nPhiladelphia Reading Iron and\nCoal is being revived in connec\ntion with the strength in Na\ntional Power and Light, National,\nit is said, would benefit from\ncheap power it could generate\nfrom anthracite waste. Electric\nBond also is said to be active.\nNational is selling at well over 20\ntimes earnings.\nI hear the heat knocked the\nspots out of department stores\nsales this month.\nGeneral Motors has been the\nbest acting stock the past few\ndays. Wilmington interests are\nsaid to be behind the move. There\nare also reports of investment\nbuying.\nPackard will have to make\nsome real money the rest of this\nyear to earn its dividend. If it\ncan\u2019t do it in automobile it will\nhave to sell, a lot of its airplane\nDiesel Motors, of which less has\nbeen heard lately.\nKennecott and American Smelt\ning are said to be under\naccumulation.\nDONI. FINANCE\nEXPANSION\nArthur E. Montgomery, presi\ndent Continental Finance Cor\nporation, a New Jersey corpora\ntion, operating under small loan\nI act, reports that despite the\n1 slump of business in general, the\nsmall loan business everywhere\nhas gone on uninterrupted.\ni The volume of new loans made\nby Continental total $323,744 for\nthe first six months ending June\n30. compared with $254,342 for\nthe same period as of last year,\n'an increase of 27.3 per cent.\nI Loans outstanding as of June 30,1\nj 1929, have increased from $317.- i\ni 428 to $516,034 as of the close of.\ni business on June 30, 1930, a 62.5 t\nper cent gain. Gross earnings\nfor the six months ending Tune\n30 increased from $47,962 in 1929\nto $82,877 in 1930, or 72.8 per\ncent.\nCanada Considers\nHighway to Alaska\nPreliminary surveys on the Can-\nada-Alaska Highway and estimates\nto determine its cost are about to\nbe started by the Victoria public\nworks department, according to\nCommerce Department advices\nfrom Vancouver yesterday.\nTwo surveying parties will be\nat work, one at Telegraph Creek\nand the other at Hazelton. The\nroad is to connect Seattle and the\nroad systems of the Pacific Coast\nwith Alaska. I\ntab\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nSailing\n\nH?\n'Am b\u00dfu. AMfck y,\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nEDWARD J. McQUADE\nVICE PRESIDENT of the Lib\nerty National Bank, who plans\nto sail on Saturday from New\nYork for the West coast. Upon\ncompletion of his journey, which\nwill include passage of the\nPanama Canal, the banker\nwill return East by rail.\nDEMES UP\nON PACKARO\nFollowing the breaking of all\nJune records in both the delivery\nof new cars to customers and\nshipments from the Packard fac\ntories, the rate of delivery and\nshipments of Packard cars is\nkeeping up to the same high\nlevels thus far in July, say offi\ncers of the Packard Motor Car\nCompany.\nPackard deliveries and ship\nments in June exceeded those for\nany other June in the 31 years\nof the company\u2019s history.\nEnjoin Trust From\nSelling Stock\nStandard Oil shares of Amer\nica. Inc., the first management\ntrust to have its business meth\nods questioned as a result of ques\ntionnaires sent out to invest\nment trusts last May by the\nState Bureau of Securities, was\nenjoined yesterday from further\nsale of securities by Supreme\nCourt Justice Strong in Brooklyn\non motion of Attorney General\nWard. A receiver will be ap\npointed.\nLOCAL STOCKS\n(Furnished by W, B Hibbs A Co.)\nSALES\nWashington Gas 6s A, sl.ooo@\n103%.\nWashington Gas 6s B. 100\n103%.\nCapital Traction Co., 9@67.\nLanston Monotype, 2@115, 8@\n112, 10@U2 100112.\nPeople\u2019s Drug Stores pfd., 5@\n103%.\nMerchants Transfer and Stor\nage pfd., 5@97.\nMergenthaler Linotype, 3@97.\nAFTER CALL\nCommercial National Bank, 7@\n225.\nCapital Traction ss, sl,ooo@\n94%..\nN. W. Steamboat rts., 7 @l6.\nPublic Utility Bonds I Bid Ask\nAm T T 4s .|10\u00bb I\nAm T T 4%s 1166\nAm T A T C Tr 5s |105%\nAnacostia A Pot R R 8i.... M I\nAna A Pot Guar 5s I 92%|\nC 4 P Tel of Va 5s 1102\nCap Trac R R 5s 94 I 94%\nCity A Suburb 5s I 80 I 8.1\nGeorgetown Gas Ist 5s 110241104\nPot Elec Cons 5s |102%|\nPot Elec 5s .1107 j\nWash Alex Mt V cts I 5 I\nWash Balt A An 5s 50 i6O\nWash Gas 5s 1103*41104%\nWash Gas \u00abs A |lO3 '103%\nWash Gas 5s B 1106 1108%\nWash Ry A Elec 4s 87 *4l 89\nMiscellaneous Bonds I\nBarber A Ross Inc \u00ab%s I 89 I 90\nChevy Chase Club 5%s 1100 1....\nD C Paper Mfg 6s 60 I 75\nW M Cold Storage 6s I 95 I\nWash Cons Title 6s I 90 iIOO\nPublic-Utility Stocks I\ndAmer Tel A Tel ~..')214%\nCapital Traction Co 67 67%\n\u2022Wash Gas Lt Co 1122 130\ndN A W Steamboat. ..|215 255\nNAW Steamboat rts 16 16%\nPot Elec Power 6s pfd 11l 112%\nPot Elec Pwr 5%s pfd 108% 109%\nWash Ry A El Com 550\nWash Ry A El pfd I 98 99\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving Its Main Office in Washington\nMEMBERS-\n4\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of. Trade\nAmerican Bankers Association\nDistrict Bankers Association\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 05<0 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nWorld Wheat Seen\nAt Average of Last\nYear\u2019s Crop Output\nWhile the Federal Farm Board\nis struggling with the problem\nj of Reclining wheat prices and is\nI assailed for its inability to sta\nbilize prices, the Department of\nAgriculture announced today indi\ncations were that the world sub\nply of what for the 1930-31 sea\nson probably would be the same\nas it was last year.\nThere is a possibility, however,\nthat it might be 100,000,000\nbushels in txcess if yields in\nthe southern hemisphere, which\ncannot now be forecast, should\nbe about average instead of low,\nas they were last year.\nAs the carry-over from last\nseason is about 100,000,000 bushels\nless than a year ago, this de\ncrease wpuld offset the increase\nin the crop.\nPrices of cash wheat in the\nUnited States are now about 50\ncents per bushel lower than they\nwere a year ago, and these low\nprices will tend to stimulate the\nuse of whegt for food and, in\nmany countries, to increase\nhuma'h consumption. Increased\nconsumption is likely to be aug\nmented by improvement in busi\nness conditions, the report said.\nThis report said:\n\u201cWith total supplies about\nequal to those of last year, in\ncreases in consumption would\nfurther reduce the world carry\nover. World trade of the com\ning year will probably be in\ncreased not only by augmented\nconsumption, but also through\nimporting countries building up\ntheir stocks. Reports thus far\nin July indicate that world\ntrade is already beginning to\nrecover from recent low levels.\nThe present burdensome carry\nover had its origin in the large\nworld crop of 1927-28, which re\nsulted in a large carryover into\nthe crop year 1928-29. Very\nlarge crops in 1928-29 greatly\nincreased the already large\ncarryover, and the world carry\nover last year was by far the\nlargest on record. A year ago,\nhowever, it had become evident\nthat the wheat crop of Canada\nand the spring wheat crop of\nthe United States would be\nsmall, and the wheat trade gen\nerally recognized that the world\ncrop of 1929-30 would be com\nparatively small.\n\u201cThat that time it appeared\nthe small crop might result in\nthe amount carried over in the\n1930-31 crop being reduced to\nI Bid I Ask\nNational Bank Stocks I\nCapita! ...\u2018.1230 250\nColumbia 400 i 475\nCommercial (stamped) 1225 240\nDistrict 1213 250\nFederal-American 1275 '3OO\nLiberty 1205 220\nLincoln 1400 1440\nMetropolitan 1350 390\nRiggs 14'8 526\nSecond 1175 1216\nWashington 1245 260\nTrust Company Stocks I\nAmer Sec A Tr Co 1378 '415\nContinental Trust 1120 1140\nMerch Bk A Tr 1125 1150\n\u2022National Sav A Trust.... 1545 6no\n\u2022Union Trust 1245 1275\nWash Loan A Tr |46a 1510\nSavings Bank Stocks I I\nBank of Bethesda 59 65\nCom A Savings 1330 I\nEast Washington I 25 j 35\nPot Savings Bank ....I 65 75\nSec Bav A Com Bk 1471 1500\nSeventh Street .....1315 I\nUnited States .....1530 I\nWash Mechanics I 50 t\nFire Insurance Stocks I I\n\u2022American 1316 f\n\u2022Corcoran 1150 |2OO\nFiremen's I 36 40\nNational Union I 22 I 26\nTitle Insurance Stocks I I\nColumbia I 8%l 12\nReal Estate 1155 |175\nTitle A Inv Co Md com... I 20 I 30\nMiscellaneous Stocks I I\nBarber A Rosa Inc com... 15 I 18\nChecy Ch Dairy pfd 103 109\nCol Sand A Grav pfd 89 I 94\nD. C. Paper Mfg pfd 10\nDfst Natl Sec pfd 73 I 55\nEmer Bromo Selz A I 30 I 35\nFederal Storage pfd TlO 1125\nFed-Am Co com (1.20f)...l 30*41 23\nFed-Arn Co pfd 99 |lO2\nLanston Monotype.....\u2019 1111 1115\nMer Tr A Stge com *lO5 110\nMer Tr A Stgs pfd I 9j*,|tlo9\nMergenthaler Lino j 95%| 97%\nNatl Mtge A Inv pfd 6 0',4\nPeoples Drug Stores bfd....U03 1104%\nReal Est M A G pfd I 6%|\nSecurity Storage 1112 1114\nTer Ref A Wh Corp I 47 52\nThe Carpel Corp 22% 24\nW Meeh Mtg com I 9%| 10\nWash Med Bldg Corp....| .\u20193 I\nWdwd A Lothrop pfd <lO5 1112\n\u2022Extra dividend.\ndex-rights.\nTho JVotfowol Ootfy\nabout normal levels. .However,\na combination of circumstances,\nincluding a worldwide business\ndepression accompanied by fall\ning prices of all commodities,\nrestrictions placed by many im\nporting countries upon wheat\nImports from other parts of\nthe world, the decline in sil\nver exchange, and large crops\nof other foodstuffs and of food\ngrains in Europe, resulted In a\nreduction in the amount of\nwheat consumed during the\npast year and in an even\ngreater reduction in the amount\nof wheat which the importing\ncountries have taken from other\nparts of the world.\n\u201cAs the 1929-30 crop season\nwas drawing to a close, the\nrealization that wheat stocks\nin exporting countries had not\nbeen reduced to normal levels,\nadded to the discouragement of\nan already over-burdened wheat\ntrade, and prices in the United\nStates have sagged to the\nlowest levels since 1914.\n\u201cDespite the world-wide busi\nness depression and other un\nfavorable circumstances, last\nyear\u2019s carry-over has been re\nduced about 100,000,000 bush\nels. If the world crop should\nturn out as now seems prob\nable, a total disappearance\nequalWo last year\u2019s would leave\nthe carry-over about the same\nnext July as it is this year, but\nit doe* not seem likely that\nthe combination of circum\nstances which resulted in a\nreduced wheat consumption dur\ning the past year will again\nhold consumption to as low a\nlevel. Both a recovery from\nthe present business depression\nand the normal upward trend\nin world wheat consumption\nare likely result in an in\ncreased use of wheat.\u201d\nI. M. B. Six Month 9 8\nNet Gains 13.7%\nNet earnings of the Interna\ntional Business Machines Corpora\ntion for the six months ended\nJune 30, 1930, amounted to\n$3,654,310 after all charges, equal\nto $5.73 a share on the. 637.954\nshares of no-par stock outstand\ning, against $3,213,601, or $5.04\na share, on the same capitaliza\ntion in the first half of 1929. This\nis an increase of 13.7 per cent.\nFor the quarter ended June 30,\n1930, net earnings were $2,089,-\n856, against' $2,019,443 for the\nthree months ended March *3l,\n1930.\nOffer $1,000,000\nBirmingham Bonds\nAn additional issue of \u201951,000,-\n000 Birmingham Chis Company\nfirst mortgage gold bonds, 5 per\ncent series due May 1, 1959,\npriced at 97 and accrued interest\nto yield about 5.20 per cent, are\nbeing offered by a banking group\nincluding W. C. Langley and\nCompany.\nOur Congratulations\nto 20,000\nGovernment Employees!\nThanks to the Act of Congress recently signed\nby the President, you will begin this month to\nreceive the increase of salary provided therein.\nOn July 31 you will determine whether it will\nbe of lasting benefit to you or not.\nIf you determine to set aside some of your\nraise in a savings account, it will prove to be a\nworth-while step\u2014a raise in self-respect, in\ncash capital and in the will to succeed.\nWe invite you to use\neither of our offices\nThe Washington Loan and Trust Company\nJOHN B. LARNER, President\nMP\nMain Office West End Office\nF and Ninth St*. Seventeenth and G St*.\nRESOURCES NINETEEN MILLION DOLLARS\nWEDNESDAY, JULY 80, 1080\n[BROKERS WARN\nOFBEAGTION\nIN MART\nDecline to Be Purely Techni\ncal Nature; Profit-taking\nIs Advised by Traders\nNEW YORK, July 30.\u2014A mild\ntechnical reaction was forecast\nin brokerage circles for today\u2019s\nsession. The taking of profits\nand the buying of leading stocks\non all dips was generally advised.\nIf some sort of reaction should\ntake place today it should not\nbe viewed with alarm or concern\nbecause it would be logical.\u2014\nBAAR, COHEN 8c CO.\nRecommend some profit taking\npending demonstration of the\nability of the leading issues to\ngain ground after the wide up\nward movements during rectal\nweeks.\u2014TO\u00dfEY <Sc KIRK.\nAdvises Holding On\nWould hold stocks already\nbought, feeling that the failure\nof the market to rally substan\ntially yesterday will leave it in a\nstronger technical position than\nwe had originally anticipated.\u2014\nHORNBLOWER <fc WEEKS.\nSuggest that active traders\nwatch early dealings carefully\nfor signs of selling. If this is\nthe case he would be more cau\ntious.\u2014OTlS CO.\nAn irregularly higher market is\nforecast, but special moves today\nmay be held in abeyance pend\ning the publication of the United\nStates Steel report for the first\nhaIf.\u2014CUSICK, KENT CO.\nStocks Called Tired\nWould limit new commitments\nat this time, since we feel that a\nreaction is in order.\u2014JOHN MEL\nADY CO.\nThe list displayed some evidence\nof fatigue today. On the whole\nhowever the tone was firm and\nthere did not seem to be any\ndisposition to liquidate.\u2014M. J.\nMEEHAN CO.\nBelieve that trading lines can\nbe increased this morning but\nwe would carry stop loss orders\non all trading stock bought just\nbelow Saturday\u2019s prices.\u2014\nEMANUEL CO.\nContinue to advise purchases\non all reactions as the market\nstill indicates accumulation.\u2014\nJOHN MUIR CO.\nA. T. T, Cuts Phone\nRates to So. Am. $6\nA reduction of $6 will be made\non telephone calls between North\nand South America on August 1,\nthe American Telephone and\nTelegraph Company announced.\nThe new rate for a conversa\ntion between New York and\nBuenos Aires will be S3O for the\nfirst three minutes and $lO for\neach additional minute, instead\nof $36 and sl2, respectively. The\nzone charges for calls between\nmore distant points on both con\ntinents will remain as at present.\nReturns\ni\nAl I\nhl\ni\n\u2014Times Staff Photo\nLAWRENCE A. SLAUGHTER\nPRESIDENT of the Commercial\nNational Bank, who has re\nturned from a vacation trip to\nthe South. Mr. Slaughter was\naway from his work for a short\ntime, but immediately asumed\nhis duties upon his return,\nNOTE INCREASE\nIN PHONES\nTelephones in the District of\nColumbia, Maryland, Virginia and\nWest Virgiriia were increased uy\n16,578 during the six months that\nended June 30, according to an\nannouncement by the officials of\nthe Chesapeake and Potomac\nTelephone Company.\nOn June 30 there were 635,447\ntelephones operated by the com\npany in the territories named, as\ncompard with 600,256 which were\nin service on the same date last\nyear.\nNot only was there an increase\nin the number of telephones, but\nthe number of originating tele\nphone calls increased from 523,-\n975.000 for the first six months of\n1929 to 538,898,000 during the\nfirst six months of this year. In\nWashington telephones have been\nincreased 3,048 since January 1,\nmaking 161,961 in service since\nJune 30. Originating telephone\ncalls In the District during the\nfirst six months of this year num\nbered 108,192,000, an increase of\n1,205,000 over the same period\nlast year.\nMidland Steel Net\nDrops to $1,267,996\nMidland Steel Products Com\npany today reported for the six\nmonths ended June 30 net earn\nings of $1,267,996, compared with\n$2,343,188 in the corresponding\n1929 period.\nLOANS INDICATE\nDECOVERY IN\nBUSINESS\nPresident of Large Industrial,\nBank Sees Restocking as\nSure Sign of Upswing\nThe recovery of business Is\nnearing, loans being made in the\nindustrial banking field indicate,\nJacob Leichtman, president of the\nModem Loan and Investment\nCorporation, second largest in\ndustrial bank in the State of\nNew York, said today,\n\u201cMerchants tell us that their\nsupplies are very low,** he said.\n\u201cThey are coming to us to bor\nrow money for restocking and\neven expanding their inven\ntories in anticipation of in\ncreased business. And manu\nfacturers, to meet these de\nmands, are asking for loans to\nincrease production activity,\nwhich has been rigidly limited\nto immediate requirements. This\ncondition has been reflected,\nnot emphatically but percept\nibly, in the loans the merchants\nand manufacturers are making\nand requesting.\n\u201cThe trend was already no\nticeable in June. That month\nthe loans of our company\namounted to $1,500,000 distri\nbuted over 4,500 loans as com\npared with $1,300,000 for 4,200\nloans for same month last year,\nand while loans are made to\nwage earners as well as small\nmerchants and manufacturers\nthe increase, even allowing for\nnatural expansion in our busi\nness, can be largely attributed\nto loans of the latter class. And\nthis month, if loans continue at\nthe rate to date, promises to be\nthe largest in our history, due\nlargely to an increase in loans\nto small merchants and manu\nfacturers.\n\u201cMore significant perhaps\neven than the increase in total\nloans is the fact that the usual\nratio between loans to wage\nearners and loans to small mar\nchants has been slightly upset in\nfavor of the latter class of\nloans. Usually, our loans aver\nage about 4 per cent to mer\nchants and manufacturers and\n60 per cent to industrial bor\ntowers or wage earners, but dur\ning last month and this month\nthe usual 40 per cent of loans\nto merchants and manufactur\ners has increased appreciably.**\nCathie\nHas a\nDream\nI IKE every lovely, inns\ncent, romantic girl of\neighteen, Cathie Paige,\nheroine of the greateat\nserial story of the year, has\ndreams of what her future\nmay hold. Reading her story\nyou\u2019ll hope her dreams come\ntrue. Follow the career of\nthis typical American girl\nday by day in\nLUCKY\nGIRL**\nBy HAZEL LIVINGSTON\nAuthor of \"Stolen Love\"\n\nwhich will be published In\ndaily installments starting\nAugust 4th in the\nNEWS\nIn Today\u2019s\nCLASSIFIED ADS\nLOCATION, as to view, coolness\nand accessibility to beech. Is most\nessential in a shore cottage. My\nhome on the water at Bay Ridge\npossesses all 'these things and Is\nvery complete and attractive tn\nevefy detail. For sale at a sacri\nfice.\nFURNISHED APARTMENT Lo\ncated oa lath St. N. W.; 3 large,\nfront rooms and bath, third floor;\nheat and light, IM.\nWHIPPET\u2014Latest ISJB Sport Road\nster: original duco; rumble seat,\nspecial set sport wheels, all good\nballoon tires; sacrificed; 8360;\nnew car terms.\nNORTH BEAChTmD.\u2014Nicely fur\nnished four-room bungalow, screened\nsleeping-porch; rent by month or\nless; available now.\nFURNISHED ROOMS\u2014B4B month-\nI, t rooms, kitchen ahd bath;\ncomplete for housekeeping; near\nGovernment departments; ideal\nplace for children; free gas and\nWIWCKCTCgnj e\nINSTRUCTION iu\u201dFrench and Ber\nman; terms medemte: ran arrange\ntn mmhd) atndant mm 11 inaSemo\nwWWu-\nlor between 4 and S p. as.\nFSase ore OS some e* *vwy\nmrsrwtmy odeortueweet* poo wdf 'nsd re\ntodep s Thm* and Arnold Omstfted Ad*.","height":"30476","width":"24410"}}
